Tumor Mutation Burden Comparison of Calculations

C. Savonen for ALSF CCDL

2019

Objectives

Compare D3b and CCDL TMB calculations as a response to this GitHub comment.

This includes CCDL TMB calculations that used mutation sets with FoCR-defined nonsynonymous filter and maftools-defined nonsynonymous filter.

We generally treat CCDLs maftools-defined filtered dataset as the benchmark since its the TMB currently in the data release (as of 09-09-2020).

These TMB datasets compared here are obtained by running:

bash analyses/snv-callers/explore_variant_classifications/run_explorations.sh

Summary of findings:

Mutation counts seem to be fairly related but the bed sizes are very different and that seems to be whats causing the differences in TMB calculations ranges. CCDL TMB is a much larger range (0 - ~300), while D3B TMB is smaller range (0 - ~5) because the BED size for CCDL TMB is much smaller than the BED size for D3B TMB.

Usage

To run this from the command line, use:

Rscript -e "rmarkdown::render('analyses/tmb-compare/compare-tmb-calculations.Rmd', 
                              clean = TRUE)"

This assumes you are in the top directory of the repository.

Setup

# magrittr pipe
`%>%` <- dplyr::`%>%`

Declare names of input and output directories.

data_dir <- file.path("..", "..", "data")
scratch_dir <- file.path("..", "..", "scratch")

Custom function for plotting the TMB.

source(file.path("util", "cdf-plot-function.R"))

Set up consensus data

Read in the three consensus TMB files.

This is the main TMB that is used in other downstream results.

tmb_ccdl_maftools <- data.table::fread(file.path(
  "..",
  "snv-callers",
  "results",
  "consensus",
  "pbta-snv-mutation-tmb-coding.tsv"
))

This is the FoCR-defined filter TMB results.

tmb_ccdl_focr <- data.table::fread(file.path(
  "..",
  "snv-callers",
  "results",
  "focr_filter",
  "pbta-snv-mutation-tmb-coding.tsv"
))

This is the d3b calculated results.

tmb_d3b <- data.table::fread(file.path(
  "TMB_d3b_code",
  "outputs",
  "pbta-snv-consensus-TMB_intarget.txt"
))

Combine the three datasets into one data.frame.

all_tmb <- tmb_ccdl_maftools %>% 
  dplyr::inner_join(tmb_ccdl_focr, by = "Tumor_Sample_Barcode", 
                    suffix = c("_maftools", "_focr")) %>% 
  dplyr::inner_join(tmb_d3b, by = "Tumor_Sample_Barcode") %>% 
  dplyr::rename(tmb_d3b = TMB, 
                mutation_count_d3b = count)

Fraction differences in TMB

Here we use the CCDLs maftools-defined filtered TMB for the denominator since its the current TMB.

Calculate fraction differences in relation to maftools-defined filtered TMB.

all_tmb <- all_tmb %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(frac_diff_focr = (tmb_maftools - tmb_focr) / tmb_maftools, 
                frac_diff_d3b = (tmb_maftools - tmb_d3b) / tmb_maftools)

Lets plot the distribution of fraction differences from both d3b and focr-defined TMBs.

all_tmb %>% 
  dplyr::select(dplyr::starts_with("frac_diff")) %>% 
  tidyr::gather("tmb_calculation_set", "frac_diff") %>%
  dplyr::mutate(tmb_calculation_set = gsub("frac_diff_", "", tmb_calculation_set)) %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(x = frac_diff, color = tmb_calculation_set)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_density() + 
  ggplot2::theme_classic() + 
  ggplot2::ggtitle("Fraction difference in TMB in comparison to CCDL maftools-defined TMB")

Most of the D3b TMBs are very different. Most of the FoCR-defined TMB are not too different but theres some with big differences.

Well investigate these a bit. Lets identify which samples have the biggest differences for FoCR-defined TMB.

all_tmb %>% 
  dplyr::filter(abs(frac_diff_focr) > .05) %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(desc(frac_diff_focr))

TMB is very different between CCDL and D3b calculations fraction wise. The ranges for the CCDL sets and the D3b sets are very different.

cat(
  " Range for CCDL maftools-defined TMB:", range(all_tmb$tmb_maftools), "\n",
  "Range for CCDL focr-defined TMB:", range(all_tmb$tmb_focr), "\n",
  "Range for D3b TMB:", range(all_tmb$tmb_d3b)
  )
 Range for CCDL maftools-defined TMB: 0.02799756 324.1557 
 Range for CCDL focr-defined TMB: 0.02799756 318.0243 
 Range for D3b TMB: 0 5.348131

Lets split up the TMB fraction to see where this vast difference in ranges might be.

How different are mutation counts?

Lets take a look at the numerator of the TMB fraction by selecting the counts columns only.

counts_only <- all_tmb %>% 
  dplyr::select(mutation_count_focr, mutation_count_maftools, mutation_count_d3b)

# Print this out
counts_only

Lets plot these counts correlations, but turn them into log1p values for easier visualization.

counts_only %>%
  dplyr::transmute_all(log1p) %>%
  GGally::ggpairs(mapping = ggplot2::aes(alpha = 0.05)) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

The samples with high TMB, still usually have a higher TMB in the other datasets.

Lets take a closer look at two of the comparisons. Heres comparing the FoCR counts to the D3B counts, which should use the same criteria for inclusion.

counts_only %>%
  dplyr::transmute_all(log1p) %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(x = mutation_count_focr, y = mutation_count_d3b)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point() + 
  ggplot2::geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") + 
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

The FoCR count always greater than or equal to the D3B count, despite the fact that these should be using the same criteria and data files. (The maftools count is also strictly greater than or equal to the FoCR count, as expected by its broader criteria for inclusion.)

Heres comparing the maftools counts to the D3B counts.

counts_only %>%
  dplyr::transmute_all(log1p) %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(x = mutation_count_maftools, y = mutation_count_d3b)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point() + 
  ggplot2::geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") + 
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

Lets take a closer look at the samples with larger differences in counts. Well compare things with mutation_count_maftools since that is what is in the current consensus file.

all_tmb %>%
  dplyr::transmute(
    Tumor_Sample_Barcode,
    ccdl_filter_diff = mutation_count_maftools - mutation_count_focr,
    ccdl_filter_diff_frac = ccdl_filter_diff / (mutation_count_maftools +1), 
    d3b_diff = mutation_count_maftools - mutation_count_d3b,
    d3b_diff_frac = d3b_diff / (mutation_count_maftools +1)
    ) %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(desc(ccdl_filter_diff))

Some of the HGAT samples are the ones with the biggest differences in counts.

How different are BED sizes?

Lets take a look at the denominator of TMB.

Both CCDL TMBs use the same bed regions so it doesnt matter if we use region_size_focr or region_size_maftools.

all_tmb %>%
  dplyr::rename(ccdl_bed_size = region_size_focr, d3b_bed_size = bedlength) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(ccdl_bed_size, d3b_bed_size, experimental_strategy) %>%
  dplyr::tally()

So the bed sizes are very different and that seems to be whats causing the differences in TMB calculations.
